{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_rigoletto_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608786/1958060701/0557.xml":{"full_text":"$3 Billion Aid Bill\nSent to Conference\nContinued From First Pace\nbe more successful in cutting\nthe money bill than they were\nIn trying to trim the authorised\nceiling last night.\nISM Million Cut Beaten\nSenator Ellender, Democrat\nof Louisiana/ was beaten in\nattempts to cut another |SOO\nmillion below the committee\nbill. By a vote of 47 to 35. he\nwas blocked in proposing a\nS3OO million reduction. He also\nlost on a voice vote when he\ntned to eliminate the Presi\ndent\u2019s S2OO million emergency\nfund.\nSenator Ellender succeeded,\n43-to-28, in lowering the ceiling\non direct military aid from 11.8\nbillion to $1.6 billion. But this\ndid not actually reduce the\noverall amount in the bill. It\nmerely means that S2OO mil\nlion of the cut the committee\nhad already made must come\nfrom military aid. The com\nmittee had given the President\nauthority to decide whether to\napply the cut to direct military\naid or to defense support.\nDefense support is aid the\nUnited States gives a country\nto enable it to maintain its\nmilitary forces.\nThe Senate spent several 1\nSlain Man\nTortured,\nProbe Finds\nNEW YORK, June 7 (IP).\u2014\nDistrict Attorney Prank 8.\nHogan says Samuel Wolkoff,\nslain trucking executive, had no\nappointment with the prosecu\ntor\u2019s office.\nWolkoff, 42, had told his wife\nThursday that he would be\nhome late because he had to\nsee a detective from the dis-j\ntrict attorney\u2019s office.\nThe Brooklyn man was found\nstrangled to death yesterday on\nManhattan\u2019s West Side. An\nautopsy performed by Dr. Mil\nton Helpern, medical examiner,\ndisclosed that Wolkoff had met\na horrible death.\n\u201cHe suffered for hours,\u201d Dr.\nHelpern said. \u201cThere were\nhemorrhages of the eyes and\nof the back of the tongue. Bits\nof hemp clung to the neck.\n\"All this indicates that who\never strangled him alternately\ntightened and loosened the rope\nover a period of hours.\u201d\nBaffled police said prelimi\nnary investigation uncovered\nno motive for the crime.\nThe victim's wallet was miss\ning, but a ring, wrist watch and\ncigarette lighter were un\ntouched and police were in\nclined to discount robbery as a\nmotitve.\nMr. Hogan announced:\n\u201cThere is no basis for the\nremark attributed to the de\nceased that he had an appoint\nment with a representative\nof this office.\n\u201cA thorough check reveals\nthat he was not known to any\none in this office and had no\nbusiness of any kind with this\noffice.\u201d\nCurious Barred\nIn Tornado Area,\nBurials Start\nMENOMONIE, Wis., June 7\n(ff). This tornado-stricken\nsection began to bury its dead\ntoday behind the protection of\nroadblocks thrown up to turn\nback the curious.\nThe barricades went up last\nnight on the order of Gov.\nVernon Thomson who said he\nwanted to close off the area to\nmorbid curiosity seekers who\nsought to explore the commu\nnities ravaged Wednesday\nnight by three tornadoes that\nclaimed 28 lives.\nSightseers threatened for a\ntime to swamp the area, but\nafter the roadblocks went up\nthe traffic thinned to a trickle\nof authorized vehicles.\nWhile recovery work went\nahead, funeral services were\nscheduled today for three of\nthe victims. Two of them were\nkilled in Colfax, hardest hit\ncommunity w-here 12 died.\nAdditional funerals will be\nheld tomorrow and Monday.\nDetective Fells Man\nIn Running Gun Fight\nA man was in critical condition and a police\ndetective hospitalized after a running gun battle last night\nin Northwest Washington.\nPolice identified the critically-wounded man as George\nBullock, of the first block of W street N.W., who was felled with\nthree bullet wounds in his abdomen, left shoulder and left arm\nDetective John D. Thompson. 34. of the Juvenile Bureau\u2019\nwas treated at Freedmen\u2019s\nHospital for a broken foot,\nwhich was shattered by another\nbullet, according to police.\nFound Argument\nCapt. John L. Sullivan said\nthe incident began with Detec\ntive Thompson and Detective\nOliver E. Brown were cruising\nin ther police car on First\nstreet N.W. near U street. No\nticing a group of three men\narguing in the street beside an\nauto, they stopped and advised\nthem to get out of the roadway.\nBullock, police said, there-1\nupon cursed Detective Thomp\nson. who got out of the pas-!\nsenger side of the police car. 1\nStanding less than a yard from\nthe officer Bullock pulled a 1\npistol out of his pocket, accord-1\ning to Capt. Sullivan, and fired I\ntwice, striking Detective!\nThompson's foot.\nPolice said Bullock turned\nand raced on foot toward V\nstreet with the detective pair in\npursuit. Detectiva Thompson\nA\nhours debating the policy state\nment in support of India.\nSenators Bridges and Dirk\nsen, Republicans of Illinois,\nargued that to single out one\ncountry by name in the dec\nlaration of policy would be a\nslap at all the other countries\nreceiving American aid.\nOthers Mentioned\nBut Senator Kennedy replied\nthat many other countries, in\ncluding Cambodia, Laos, Viet\nNam and Yugoslavia, have\nbeen mentioned in other parts\nof the mutual security act.\nSenator Kennedy insisted\nthat India is the key to what\nhappens to all of Asia outside\nof Red China. He was joined\nin defense of aid to India by\nSenator Cooper, Republican of\nKentucky, who was American\nAmbassador to India several\nyears ago.\nCritics of India\u2019s Prime Min\nister Nehru called him a Com\nmunist, but Senator Cooper said\nthe charge was not true. The\nKentuckian told his colleagues\na real struggle is going on in\nAsia, which has a third of the\nworld\u2019s population, and that\nIndia is the only countrj in\nAsia that could stand up to\nRed China.\nLABOR\nt\nContinued From First Page\ncampaigns to Impose some\ncriminal responsibility on un\nions that keep violators of re\nporting requirements in office\nand to require 15 days notice\nof union elections.\nIn another action, the com\nmittee resolved to urge the Ap\npropriations Committee to in\ncrease funds for the National\nLabor Relations Board to han\ndle types of labor cases that\nagency has dropped.\nSenator Kennedy told re- j\nporters the tightened measure\nis \u201can extremely strong and es- j\nfective bill (which) carries out;\nevery one of the live recom\nmendations of the McClellan\nCommittee completely.\u201d He was\noptimistic about prospects for\npassage by the Senate.\nHouse Plans Hearings\nEven if the Senate does pass\nithe bill, the House Labor Com-]\nmittee may block final enact-]\nment. It plans to hold hearings\nwell into July.\nSenator McClellan indicated\nhe will press for stronger legis\nlation next year. Crediting the\npending bill largely to dis\nclosures by his Rackets Com-1\nmittee, he commented: \u201cWe\nhave not closed shop (and).\nwill continue to investigate and i\nexpose that which Congress\nneeds to know to guide it in\nfurther legislation.\u201d\nKey Provisions\nKey provisions of the com\nmittee bill would:\n1. Require unions to report\nto the Government on their\nfinances, and officers to report\non possible conflicts of interest.\n2. Limit use of trusteeships to\ncontrol local unions to 18\nmonths unless the parent na\ntional union can prove the need\nto continue running the local.\n3. Require election of union\nofficers by secret ballot or by\ndelegates chosen by secret\nballot.\n4. Limit terms of local offi\ncers to four years and national\nofficers to five years.\n5. Bar anyone convicted of\nmajor crimes from holding\nunion office.\n6. Prohibit organizational\ni picketing for extortion.\n7. Allow strikers to vote in\nrepresentation elections.\n8. Repeal the requirement\nfor union officers to file non-\nCommunist affidavits.\n9. Require employers and\nmanagement \"middlemen\" to\nreport on improper labor ac\ntivities.\n10. Make embezzlement of\nunion funds a Federal crime,\nand tighten curbs on bribery.\n11. Impose criminal penalties\nranging as high as a SIO,OOO\njflne and five years imprison-\nI ment.\nSenator Kennedy was eager\nto dispute any feeling that the\nbill is mild. It does go be\nyond recommendations by un\nion leaders, but they prefer\nithe committee\u2019s version to\nmany other pending proposals.\nfired three shots before he\nnoticed a pam in his foot\u2014the\nfirst indication of his injury,\nthe officers reported.\nDetective Fires\nAs Detective Thompson\nlimped back to the car to radio\nfor help. Detective Brown con\ntinued in pursuit. He told\nsuperiors that, when Bullock\nreached the corner, he turned\naround, gun in hand, where\nupon the detective fired his own\nrevolver. He said he did not\nknow if Bullock's pistol dis\ncharged then or not.\nThe detective said Bullock\ni fell to the ground, but as the\nI officer reached to pick him up,\nthe wounded man struck him in\njthe face with the gun. and\nproceeded to fight until he was\nj subdued.\nBullock was taken to District\nGeneral Hospital.\nPolice were searching today\nfor his two companions who\ndisappeared during the chase.\nf\n\u2014\u2014p\u2014\nragr\n\n\ni\nwfcjS&S&f (f\nBURNING TRUCK SETS HOUSE ABLAZE\nFlaming gasoline poured from this tank truck\nwhen it overturned at an intersection in Miami\nyesterday and set the building (at top) on fire,\nLabor Chiefs Rap Ives\nOn Harriman Criticism\nNEW YORK, June 7 (JP).\u2014 i\nTwo labor leaders yesterday\n\ncriticized an accusation that;\nGov. Averell Harrimanr\u2019s official\nconduct was influenced by\nfriendship with a labor rack\neteer. 1 1\nThe charge, raised by Sena- 1\ntor Irving M. Ives, Republican\nof New York, Thursday night, j\n\u201cis an insult to us and to the\nentire labor movement,\u201d said\nHarry van Arsdale, president]\nof the New York AFL Central\nTrades and Labor Council, and\nLouis Hollander, president of\nthe State CIO.\nSenator Ives said that Gov.\nHarriman, a Democrat, vetoed\na labor rackets bill passed by\nthe Republics n-controlled\nState Legislature because \u201cone\nof his closest pals is one of the\nleading racketeers in the United\nStates.\u201d\nGov. Ives added: \u201cI put two\nand two together. I can\u2019t prove\nit at all.\u201d j]\nVan Arsdale and Hollander\ncalled a news conference to pro\ntest the Ives charge. They said\norganized labor obtained the\nveto because the bill had been i\nrushed through without hear\nings.\nFriend of Joey Faye\nFaces Racket Grilling\nThe Senate Rackets Com\nmittee looks forward to grilling\na self-styled \u201cchampion\u201d of\nunions who reportedly be\nfriended Joey Faye, a convicted\nlabor racketeer, while digging\nfor derogatory information on\nGeorge Meany, president of the\nAFL-CIO.\nHarold R. Danforth, a New\nYork prfVate detective, told the\ncommittee yesterday he was\nhired last year by Maxwell C.\nRaddock, a Yonkers (N. Y.)\npublisher of labor literature, to\nlook into Mr. Meany\u2019s past.\nMr. Raddock also wanted in\nformation to use against Wal\nter Reuther, president of the\nUnited Auto Workers, and\nDavid Dubinsky, president of,\nthe International Ladies Gar- i\nment Workers Union, Mr. Dan\nforth testified. Both men are\nAFL-CIO vice presidents.\nBut Mr. Raddock was not in- i\nterested in investigating Faye,\nPresident James R. Hofla of\nthe Teamsters Union or other i\nlabor officials who have been\ncharged with corruption, Mr. 1\nDanforth said.\n\u201cStiffening\u201d Desired\nThe reason given for investi-\ngating Mr. Meany, Mr. Dan-\nforth said, was that Mr. Rad\ndock wanted to \"stiffen his\nbackbone so he would stand up\nagainst Reuther.\u201d\nMr. Danforth collected $2,000\nfrom Mr. Raddock in two\nmonths before quitting the as\nsignment last August, he said,\nexplaining that he refused to\ncontinue because \"I didn't know\nwho he represented or what he\nwanted to use the information\nfor.\u201d\nMr. Raddock is scheduled to\ntestify next week about hiring\nthe detective and about other\nallegations including the\ncharge that he colluded with\nofficials of the United Brother-\nhood of Carpenters to split a\n$310,000 fee he received for\nwriting and publishing a book\nglorifying William L. Hutch-\neson, the late president of the\nCarpenters. Maurice A. Hutch\neson, son of William L. and now j\npresident of the Carpenters, also\nis on the witness list.\n11\nShortage Described\nThe committee also heard\ntestimony yesterday that $2,000\ndisappeared from the Carpen-\nters\u2019 treasury until staff investi-\ngators discovered the shortage.\nCommittee Counsel Robert F.\nKennedy implied the money\nwas intended tot use in oppos-\ning a right-to-work bill in the\nIndiana Legislature, but the\nbill was passed before the\nmoney could be spent. jj\nChairman McClellan called\nMr. Raddock's activities \u201cmo6t >l\nreprehensible.\" and charged he\ncolluded with officials of the\nI Carpenters to \u201cenrich them-i\nI\nThe bill required union\n(leaders to detail their finances.\nWhen he vetoed it, Harriman\nsaid the bill looked like a\nunion-busting measure.\nSenator Ives\u2019 charge was as\nmuch against labor as against\nGov. Harriman. Van Arsdale\nand Hollander said.\n1 Both labor leaders suggested\nthat Senator Ives also would\nhave vetoed the bill.\nGov. Harriman and the man\n\u2014identified as Robert Bernard\nBaker, 46, a union organizer\nwith a prison record dis\nclaimed any friendship. They\nsaid their acquaintance was\nlimited to a single handshake.\nVan Arsdale and Hollander\nsaid such labor leaders as\nhundreds of local unions 1\nthroughout the State had\ncalled for the veto.\nSenator Ives, informed of the\nVan Arsdale-Hollander state-;\nment, said:\n\u201cI didn\u2019t in any way impung\nlabor\u2019s motives in the matter.\nAil those gentlemen are re\nspectable people I won\ndered if the connection with\nBaker had anything to do with\ni the veto.\u201d\nftp\njf| J\nHAROLD DANFORTH\nselves at the expense of the\nmembers.\u201d\nMr. Kennedy yesterday ac\ncused Mr. Raddock of falsify\ning records of his publishing\ncompany, World Wide Press, to\ncover up vital details of the\nbook deal. According to earlier\ntestimony, Mr. Raddock over\ncharged the Carpenters by at\nleast $185,000, and defaulted on\ndelivery.\nBrussels Foir to See\nA Bit of Our Wild West\nThe \u201cWild West\u201d of Buffalo\nBill Cody gleamed briefly but\nhorselessly in Washington yes\nterday.\nClose to 80 cowpokes of both\nsexes touched down at National\nAirport for a breather en route\nfrom points as far away' as\nCaliforriia to put on a rootin\u2019\ntootin\u2019 American horse opera at\nthe Brussels World\u2019s Fair.\nIt will be the first time cow-\nboys and Indians have invaded\nEurope since the whiskered\nBill and sharp-shootin\u2019 Annie\nOakley had the Europeans de\nlighted with their show 70\nyears ago.\nBeing without horses\u2014they\u2019re\ntraveling by ship\u2014the troupe\nput on no show at the airport\nyesterday. Not even a \u201cYip-ee\u201d\n\u2014or whatever cowboys are ex\npected to shout\u2014pierced the\nair.\nAmong some of the talent is\nCasey Tibbs, five times world\nchampion bronco rider and\nthree times world champion all\naround cowboy.\nThe entire Eddie Faulkner t\nfamily of Caiabasas, Calif.,\nis part of the show. Eddie rides,\nbroncos and bulls and wrestles\n\u2014or wrangles\u2014cattle to the\nturf. His wife, Diggy, performs\non better mannered beasts, as\nstroying it. The driver suffered only scratches\nand bruises. A car following the truck also was\nburned.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nNEW HURRICANE\nSPOTTERST ATIONS\nBEING SET UP\nNORFOLK, Va (JP).\u2014\nThree new hurricane ob\nserver stations will\nstrengthen the area\u2019s\nweather warning system for\nthe hurricane season begin\nning June 15.\nThe stations, manned by\nvolunteer observers, are at\nVirginia Beach, Manteo\nand Nags Head. Observers\nwill make daily checks of\ninstruments and will be\navailable to give informa\ntion to regular weather bu\nreaus when a hurricane\nthreatens\nGlen V. Sachse, chief\nof the United States\nWeather bureau here, said\nthe government has\nequipped the volunteer sta\ntions with instruments to\nmeasure wind speed and\nbarometric pressure.\nMACMILLAN\nContinued From First Page\nOn Tuesday morning the Brit\nish Prime Minister, accompa\nnied by President Eisenhower,\nwill go to'Johns Hopkins Uni\nversity in Baltimore to speak.\nThey will fly by helicopter\nfrom the White House lawn.\nHis third public appearance\nwill be at a National Press Club\nluncheon Wednesday.\nLater that day Mr. Macmil\nlan flies to Ottawa for a con\nference with Canadian Prime\nMinister John Diefenbaker.\nBefore leaving London last\nnight, the British statesman\nsaid he was looking forward to\ninformal and friendly talks\nwith \u201cmy old friend, the Presi\ndent of the United States and\nwith the Prime Minister of\nCanada.\u201d He emphasized he\ndid not intend to have formal\nconferences. Instead he said\nhe would just \u201cmeet and talk\nover the different problems of\nthe day.\u201d\nThe combination of America's\nrecession and the Soviet Union\u2019s\nnew trade offensive have caused\napprehension in Great Britain.\nRepercussions of the United\nStates economic difficulties\nhave been felt in lowered levels\nof free-world trade. Many\nBritish economists think the\ntime is at hand for the United\nStates to step in with credits\nto keep trade moving\u2014before\nthe temporary setback becomes\nsevere.\nBoth Prime Minister Mac\nmillan and French Premier de\nGaulle served with Gen. Eisen\nhower in North Africa during\nWorld War 11. Gen. de Gaulle\nwas then regarded as a proud\nFrenchman hard to get along\nwith. The British and Ameri\ncan leaders are expected to\nspend some of their time map\niping a joint strategy to deal\niwith Gen. de Gaulle\u2019s expected\nmoves to strengthen French\nprestige in the world.\ndo their children. Cindy, 5. and\nBrady, a pint-size rootin\u2019 tootin\u2019\nage 2.\nHoward Pyle, deputy assistant\nto President Eisenhower, greet\ned the troupe as it sashayed\ndown the Pan American Clipper\ngangway.\nBesides displaying their skill\nwith animals in Brussels, the\nwild westerners with the help\nof some Sioux Indians will stage\nCuster\u2019s Last Stand\u2014without\nwhich any wild Western would\nbe downright subversive.\nATTENTION\nCHILDREN'S WEAR OPERATORS\nFor Lease\nWildwood Manor Shopping Center\nOld Georgetown Road and Grojvenor Lana, Bethetda, Md.\nStores available in this beautiful new shopping center\nfor gifts, children's wear, family shoes, etc. Large stores\nleased to Food Fair Supermarket Co., Peoples Drug, Blue\nRibbon Valet, Peoples Hardware, Variety Five and Ten,\nWomen's Wear, and others. Parking for over 600 cars.\nNow under construction. Possession early fall.\nConsult Leasing Dcvt\nRealtor*\n_ Exclusive Agents\n724 14th St. N.W. NA. 8-2345\nOut 53rd Anniversary Year\nI\nDE GAULLE\nContinued From First Page\nand other local administrative\nposts.\nAlthough no specific date was\nset for these elections, Mr. Mal\nraux said the aim of the cabi\nnet was to hold them in about\none month.\nThe cabinet also planned to\npromote mass demonstrations 1\nof unity throughout France on\nJune 18. This is the anniver-\nsary of the famed broadcast\nwhich Gen. de Gaulle made\nover the British Broadcasting\nCorp. network calling on Free\nFrance to continue the fight\nafter it was overrun by the\nGermans in 1940.\nThe cabinet also decided not\nto hold any elections in France\nto fill the vacant National As- j\nsembly seats before the na\ntional referendum on the con\nstitution.\nThere are about a half-dozen\nAssembly posts now vacant\nthrough deaths but the Assem\nbly is on an enforced vacation\nanyway, at Gen. de Gaulle\u2019s\ninsistence. The cabinet said\nany such special elections at\npresent would be inopportune.\nCommittee Restricted\nGen. de Gaulle in his final\nday at Oran yesterday made\nclear to the insurgent All-\nAlgeria Committee of Public\nSafety, the official name of\nthe junta, that its members\nno longer will rule in Algeria.\nThey should confine them\nselves, under Gen. Salan's di\nrection, to stepping up contacts\nbetween European and Moslem\npopulations, Gen. de Gaulle\nsaid.\nThe committees seemed in\nno mood, however, to pack up\nand leave just because Gen. de\nGaulle had spoken.\nSigns of discontent continued i\nto come from Algiers. Com\nmittee spokesman Lucien Neu-j\nwirth said the group there;\nwould give Gen. de Gaulle its:\nco-operation \u201cwithout reserve!\nor conditions.\u201d But he refused\nto say whether the committee;\napproved Gen de Oaulle\u2019s cabt- 1\nnet choices, which froze out the.\nj extreme rightists.\nAnother committee leader,\nLeon Delbecque, voiced what\nsounded like an intention to\ndefy Gen. de Gaulle if he\ndoesn\u2019t do what committee\nmembers want.\nJust how much control Gen.\nde Gaulle has established over\nthe committees and how easy\nGen. Salan would find it to re\nassert central authority were\nquestions that could not be\nanswered immediately.\nSecond Thoughts at Home\nAfter the first wave of en\nthusiasm, Frenchmen at home\nseemed to be having second\nthoughts on the desirability of\nmaking Algerians equal citi\nzens.\nThey were reminding each\nother than government figures\nshow the Algerian Moslem pop\nulation is more than 90 per\ncent illiterate and that only a\nsmall proportion speak more\nthan a smattering of French.\nArabic is the predominate\ntongue.\nIf representation is contin\nued under Gen. de Gaulle\u2019s\nforthcoming proposals for con\nstitutional reform as it has,\nbeen in the past, Algeria will,\nhave some 130 representatives\nin the French National Assem\nbly, which now numbers 596\ndeputies.\nMany feared 130 deputies, if\nunited, would hold the balance\nof power in the Assembly, thus\ngiving Algeria effective control\neven if only by veto.\nMeanwhile, French military\nheadquarters in Algiers said\nFrench units in Algeria were\nattacked yesterday by both\nTunisian troops and Algerian\nNationalist rebels based in Tu\nnisia. No casualty figures were\nreported.\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nMjTTBBAT. nmi 7. rasa\nPatman Says\nInterest Rates\nPeril Upturn\nBy tin Aaioclatsd Prm\nRepresentative Patman,\nDemocrat of Texas, chairman\nof the Senate-House Economic\nCommittee, said today high\ninterest rates are slowing eco\nnomic recovery.\nA frequent critic of adminis\ntration credit policies, Mr. Pat\nman said in an Interview there\nappears t\u00bb be \u201ca determination\nto keep Interest rates high.\"\n\u201cYou can\u2019t have recovery in\nthis country Until you reduce\nInterest rates,\u201d he added.\nMr. Patman\u2019s criticism of\nadministration monetary policy I\nj followed a report by the staff\nI of the Joint Economic Commit- j\ntee painting a gloomy picture\nof the economy. It said eco-i\nnomic recovery could not be]\nexpected before mld-1959 at\nthe earliest, and possibly not\nbefore mid-1960.\nLong Term Credit\nThe report also said mone\nary action by the Government\n\u2014control of credit and interest\nrates has not yet brought\nabout restoration of the easier\nlong-term credit that prevailed\nfrom 1951 to 1955.\nTaking a general view of the\neconomy, the report said \u201cthere j\nare as yet few signs of an early\nupturn.\u201d It said unemployment,\nby the most optimistic assump\ntions. would continue at around\n5 million to 5Mi million in the\nfirst quarter of 1959. Under less\noptimistic conditions, it added,\nthe figure could be as high as\nseven million.\nThe report found Govern\nment spending the strongest\nelement in the economy, but\nsaid it was likely to be offset\nby the decline in business\nspending on plant and equip\nment.\nMr. Patman, although oppos\ning general tax reduction ex\ncept as a last resort, said the\neconomy would get a boost\nfrom reduction cr gradual\nelimination of wartime excise\ntaxes.\nRate Ease Urged\nBut in the larger area of eco\nnomic remedial action, Repre\nsentative Patman prescribed a\nfurther easing of credit as an\ninducement to business to fi\nnance new activity\u2014principally\nin capital plant and equipment\npurchases.\nIn its analysis of the econ\nomy, the committee staff report\nsaid \u201cthe mainspring of the\npresent economic contraction\nis the sharp reduction in busi\nness spending for new plant\nUnion Meeting Follows\nTrouble at Chrysler\nDETROIT. June 7 (JP). \u2014The\nUnited Auto Workers Union\nleadership called a meeting to\nday of local union officials from\nChrysler plants in the Detroit\njarea to discuss enforcement of\n'the union\u2019s no-strike policy.\nThe union completed a full\n1 week of operating without con\ni tracts at Chrysler, General Mo\ni tors and Ford. Its 500,000 mem\nbers at the Big Three are under\norders to stay on the job and\njnot provoke strikes.\nBut trouble flared yesterday\nat Chrysler\u2019s Plymouth body\nand assembly plants here. The\ncompany shut down operations\nat both plants, idling a total\nof 5,400 workers on two shifts.\nThe company said two men\nwho had been union stewards\nunder the old contract set off\na work stoppage after they were\nlaid off for refusing work at\nassigned jobs. This resulted in\na shutdown, the company said,\nidling 1.500 workers in the body\nThe Eberly Plan\nWhat is it?\nIt is something that every\nhome owner has been looking\nfor and should know about.\nAny type of repairs, decorat\ning or remodeling of the home\nand the know-how to execute\nthem.\nWe Finance the work\u2014\nYou can poy by the month\nOur 109-Year-Old Creed\n\"Promise only what you con do, o/woyj do what you promt*'\nA. Eberly\u2019s Sons\n1108 K St. N.W. District 7-6557\n\u2014I k\nand equipmetnt plus the asso\nciated liquidation of inven\ntories, declines in consumer in\ncomes and accompanying cuts\nin consumer spending.\u201d\nAs one step, Mr. Patman said\nthe Federal Reserve rediscount\nrate should again be cut .to 1\nper cent from its present figure\nof 1% per cent. The redis\ncount rate, sometimes called\nthe wholesale cost of money, is\nthe interest charged by the Fed\neral Reserve tor borrowings by\nits member banks.\nSHOOT\nContinued From First Pago\nfirst time in the bedroom of\nthe apartment and then ran\ntoward the door.\nHomicide Squad Capt. Law\nrence Hartnett said Mrs. Ear\npino said before she died that\nj her husband had shot her\nand muttered something about\ni \u201ctrouble.\"\nThe shots resounded through\nthe apartment house, bringing\nI several neighbors to the scehe.\n'Among the first to arrive at\nthe couple\u2019s doorway were Wil\nliam Owen, an Associated Press\neditor, and William Ramberg,\n1 another seventh-floor occupant.\n\u201cI heard the shots,\u201d 'Mr.\nOwen said, \u201cbut at first I\nthought it was someone slam\nming a door. Then I heard it\nagain and ran down the hall.\nI saw the woman lying inside\nthe door and blood running on\nthe floor.\u201d\nJ. C. Blake, apartment man\nager, said the couple had lived\nat the Saxony about a yeas.\nHe said they had no children,\nwere quiet, reserved people and\nseemed happy.\nDon Carlos Chapoy, First\nSeen -ry of the Embassy, said\nMrs. Espino had been ill.\n\"Mr. Espino was reserved but\nhis concern showed through,\u201d\nj said Mr. Chapoy.\nThe First Secretary said Mr.\nEspino was a native of Mexico\nCity and had been an employe\nof the Embassy for 18 years.\nSoustelle Reports\nOfficially Denied\nALGIERS, June 7 (JP). \u2014A\nspokesman for Gen. Raoul\nSalan, the newly appointed\ndelegate in Algeria for Premier\nCharles de Gaulle, today for\nmally denied reports Jacques\nSoustelle will be given a high\ndiplomatic post.\nFrench diplomatic circles in\nWest Germany yesterday said\nthat Premier de Gaulle was\nexpected to name Mr. Soustelle,\npolitical adviser to the Algiers\nmilitary-civilian junta, as am\nbassador to Washington.\nInformed sources in Paris\nalso have discounted the report.\nplant and 1,200 in the assembly\nplant.\nA similar situation developed\nat the start of the second shift,\nthe company said. The com\npany statement said: \u201cBecause\nseveral trim department em\nployes at the Plymouth Detroit\nbody plant refused to start\nwork on the second shift it was\nimpossible for the company to\ncontinue normal operations.\u201d\nThe dispute followed Chrys\nler\u2019s decision to put into effect\nnew rules restricting the\namount of time chief stewards\nand shop committeemen can\ntake from their jobs to handle\ngrievances of UAW members.\nThe union charged the com\npany was attempting to pro\nvoke strikes by discipling minor\nunion officials in the plants.\nThe company denied this.\nNew contract negotiations,\nwhich now have to start over\nfrom scratch, are in recess un-.\ntil Monday at all Big Three\ncompanies.\nA-7","height":"29028","width":"18317"}}
